sentences: Meg Christian (born 1946 in Lynchburg, Virginia) is an American folk singer associated with the women's music movement.

She graduated from the University of North Carolina and moved to Washington, D.C. in 1969, where she performed in nightclubs and began writing material from an explicitly political and feminist perspective.

She graduated from the University of North Carolina and moved to Washington, D.C. in 1969, where she performed in nightclubs and began writing material from an explicitly political and feminist perspective.
For a time in the 1970s, Christian, who is openly lesbian, embraced women's separatism and sometimes played at women-only venues.
She ceased giving live performances in 1984, and began studying Eastern mysticism; the result of these explorations were the albums The Fire of My Love and Songs of Ecstasy.
